00:26:12.565 --> 00:26:14.205
The internet is out there, kids are using it,

577
00:26:14.205 --> 00:26:16.205
and there's nothing we can really do about that.

578
00:26:16.385 --> 00:26:18.205
The onerous bands that we've seen in Australia

579
00:26:18.225 --> 00:26:21.485
and the UK are gonna have limited efficacy because one way

580
00:26:21.485 --> 00:26:22.685
or another children are gonna still

581
00:26:22.685 --> 00:26:23.965
have exposure to the internet.

582
00:26:24.395 --> 00:26:26.805
However, there are still a large number

583
00:26:26.805 --> 00:26:28.685
of regulatory strategies that we can use.

584
00:26:28.745 --> 00:26:32.405
And also platforms do have an incentive to try

585
00:26:32.405 --> 00:26:35.045
and make their platforms commercially acceptable

586
00:26:35.045 --> 00:26:36.285
to parents and to kids.

587
00:26:36.705 --> 00:26:40.325
And so by applying the right kind of pressure, we can double

588
00:26:40.325 --> 00:26:42.045
that incentive and actually try

589
00:26:42.045 --> 00:26:43.405
and get these platforms to a place

590
00:26:43.655 --> 00:26:45.525
where the trade-offs are kind of worth it

591
00:26:45.525 --> 00:26:49.285
and where the harms versus the benefits are set at a place

592
00:26:49.285 --> 00:26:50.445
that we find tolerable,

593
00:26:50.595 --> 00:26:52.325
even if we can't get to a perfect place.

594
00:26:52.705 --> 00:26:53.705
Mm-hmm.

595
00:26:54.215 --> 00:26:56.365
Thank you Ji. Yeah, thank you.

596
00:26:56.665 --> 00:26:58.045
Uh, thanks, uh, for your submission

597
00:26:58.045 --> 00:27:00.405
and as in your submission, you have mentioned about

