00:27:21.465 --> 00:27:23.525
And then who would be then responsible for that?

606
00:27:23.625 --> 00:27:25.445
How do we kind of navigate that?

607
00:27:25.755 --> 00:27:27.685
Just keen to understand from you,

608
00:27:28.745 --> 00:27:31.845
No system you build is going to be really foolproof.

609
00:27:32.245 --> 00:27:33.925
Children are gonna figure out ways to get around it.

610
00:27:34.075 --> 00:27:36.045
Even if you do like the age assurance systems

611
00:27:36.045 --> 00:27:38.605
that Australia's thinking about, if a parent works

612
00:27:38.605 --> 00:27:40.685
with the child to get around the band, that'll still work.

613
00:27:40.685 --> 00:27:42.845
If they have an older sibling, that'll still work. Mm.

614
00:27:42.945 --> 00:27:44.725
The goal is not to make it foolproof.

615
00:27:45.025 --> 00:27:48.565
The goal is to find the right space in the in trade-offs

616
00:27:48.565 --> 00:27:50.245
of like how onerous this is

617
00:27:50.245 --> 00:27:53.125
and what kind of civilities we give up versus the efficacy.

618
00:27:53.125 --> 00:27:54.165
And the device level thing,

619
00:27:54.165 --> 00:27:55.685
at least from my lab's perspective,

620
00:27:55.685 --> 00:27:58.445
strikes a fairly nice balance between like,

621
00:27:58.475 --> 00:27:59.925
kids are gonna get around it,

622
00:28:00.185 --> 00:28:03.725
but this provides like a watchful parent a fairly good way

